Variant 1: Larger or smaller layers

Here, weâ€™ll try the whole range from \(2^2 = 4\) to \(2^{6} = 64\) neurons in each of our hidden layers.

To do this, weâ€™ll define a function, define_model that allows us to define and compile our model. It takes one argument:

  • powerto = 4 - integer, the number of neurons as defined by two to the power of this value.
# Generalise the model definitions
# Defaults to parameters we used in original case study.
define_model <- function(powerto = 4) {
  
  # cat("Defining model with ", 2^powerto, " neurons per hidden layer \n")
  
  # Define the model, using powerto arg for neuron number.
  network <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
    layer_dense(units = 2^powerto, activation = "relu", input_shape = 13) %>% 
    layer_dense(units = 2^powerto, activation = "relu") %>% 
    layer_dense(units = 1)
  
  # Compile as before
network %>% compile(
  optimizer = "rmsprop", 
  loss = "mse", 
  metrics = "mae"
)
}

In addition to that, Iâ€™ll define another function for training the model, run_model. It takes one argument:

  • epochs = 20 - integer, the numer of training epochs.

I wonâ€™t actually change the number of epochs here. itâ€™s provided for your convenience. Iâ€™ve set verbose = FALSE to avoid lots of print out.

run_model <- function(network, epochs = 20) {
  
  # cat("Training model ... \n")

  # Train the model and return the history (or just the network)
    network %>% fit(
      train_data,
      train_targets,
      epochs = epochs,
      batch_size = 512,
      validation_data = list(val_data, val_targets),
      verbose = FALSE
    )
}

The data is built into the function definitions, so calling my functions as below will provide the results weâ€™ve seen previously.

define_model() %>% 
  run_model() -> history_original 

# Plot history using default:
history_original %>%
  plot()

# Prep data frame for use later on:
history_original %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(nlayers = "2",
         powerto = "16") -> history_original

Iâ€™m using purrr::map() to calculate all the models reiteratively. Since I want to plot all the values together, I convert the history to a data frame. At the end weâ€™ll have one large data frame with a powerto column that tells use how many neurons that model used.

# Define number of neurons
powerto_input <- c(2:3,5:6)

powerto_input %>% 
  map(define_model) %>% 
  map(run_model) %>% 
  map_df(data.frame, .id = "powerto") %>% 
  mutate(powerto = as.character(factor(powerto, labels = 2^powerto_input)),
         nlayers = "2") -> history_powerto

From this, we can look at how the validation set accuracy and loss are affected. The line marked with red dots are the values we used in the original definition, above.

Compared to the differently sized layers, our model reaches a fairly high and consistent accuracy. The larger models do not improve much on our original result.

Variant 2: Changing the number of layers layers

So now we have an idea that 16 neurons is appropriate. Do you think it would help to change the number of layers? Iâ€™m going to expand on the build_model() function I established earlier to allow us to define how many hidden layers.

  • nlayers = 2 integer, the number of hidden layers. Minimum is 1.

To make my syntax with purrr::map() easier, Iâ€™m going to put it in the first position.

define_model <- function(nlayers = 2, powerto = 4) {

  # cat("Defining model with ", 2^powerto, " neurons per ", nlayers," hidden layer(s) \n")
  
  # Establish model with single hidden, input, layer
   network <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
    layer_dense(units = 2^powerto, activation = "relu", input_shape = 13)

  # Add nlayers-1 number of additional layers
  if (nlayers > 1) {
  map(2:nlayers, ~ network %>%
        layer_dense(units = 2^powerto, activation = "relu") 
  )
  }
  
  # Add final layer  
  network %>% 
    layer_dense(units = 1)
  
network %>% compile(
  optimizer = "rmsprop", 
  loss = "mse", 
  metrics = "mae"
)

}

Once again, Iâ€™ll use purrr::map() to calculate all the models reiteratively. This time Iâ€™ll have one large data frame and the nlayers column will correspond to how many layers that model contained.

# Define number of neurons
nlayers_input <- c(1,3:4)

nlayers_input %>% 
  map(define_model) %>%
  map(run_model) %>% 
  map_df(data.frame, .id = "nlayers") %>% 
  mutate(nlayers = as.character(factor(nlayers, labels = nlayers_input)),
         powerto = "16") -> history_nlayers

More layers seems to preform worse!
